Boilermech, SK Telecom, Shinhan, San Miguel: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-05-04T21:44:18Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-04/boilermech-sk-telecom-shinhan-san-miguel-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Boilermech Holding Bhd. (BMHB MK): The Malaysian
manufacturer of boilers for the palm-oil milling industry will
start trading on the Kuala Lumpur stock exchange. The company
sold shares at 33 sen each in its initial public offering,
according to its listing prospectus.  Fututech Bhd. (FUT)  : The Malaysian lighting products
supplier proposed a share capital reduction to reduce
accumulated losses and a rights offer to raise as much as 41.1
million ringgit ($13.8 million) for working capital, according
to a company statement. The shares fell 0.8 percent to 63.5 sen.  SK Telecom Co. (017670 KS):  South Korea ’s largest mobile-
phone operator forecast a 2.4 trillion won ($2.23 billion)
operating profit this year on sales of 13.3 trillion won,
according to a regulatory filing. SK Telecom added 0.6 percent
to 166,000 won.  Shinhan Financial Group Co. (055550 KS): Shinhan Financial
sees the impact on its business from the slump in the
 construction industry  as “limited” because the company had
slashed loans for real-estate projects, Chief Financial Officer
Min Jung Kee said in a teleconference. The company had 5.3
trillion won worth of so-called project financing loans as of
the end of March, the CFO said. The stock dropped 0.4 percent to
52,200 won.  San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  : Shares of the largest Philippine
food and drinks company will resume trading today after a three-
week voluntary suspension to complete the sale of shares and
convertible bonds for expansion.  San Miguel  sold common shares
at 110 pesos each. The company said May 3 that it’s yet to
determine the amount it raised from the share and debt sale,
which it estimated at $900 million on April 20. The stock sank
4.4 percent to 153 pesos when it last traded on April 12.  To contact the reporter on this story:
